   <conbody>
      <div class="- topic/div ">
         <p class="- topic/p ">If top cable entry is needed, the system will have two aluminium
plates on the top <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">(A)</b> and two aluminium at the bottom <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">(B)</b> of the system. One of the plates are placed to the front and one
to the back. For more information see the <i class="+ topic/ph hi-d/i ">Drawings</i>.</p>
      </div>
      <section class="- topic/section ">
         <title class="- topic/title ">Aluminium Cable Glad Plates</title>
         <hazardstatement id="Cable-glad-plates_Drill-contact-1CFEA304"
                          type="danger"
                          class="+ topic/note hazard-d/hazardstatement ">
            <messagepanel class="+ topic/ul hazard-d/messagepanel ">
               <typeofhazard class="+ topic/li hazard-d/typeofhazard ">HAZARD OF ELECTRIC SHOCK, EXPLOSION, OR ARC FLASH</typeofhazard>
               <howtoavoid class="+ topic/li hazard-d/howtoavoid ">
                  <sl class="- topic/sl ">
                     <sli class="- topic/sli ">Never drill or cut holes for cables or conduits with the gland
plates installed.</sli>
                     <sli class="- topic/sli ">Never drill or cut holes near the system.</sli>
                     <sli class="- topic/sli ">Never have direct contact between the cable gland plate and the
cable.</sli>
                  </sl>
               </howtoavoid>
            </messagepanel>
         </hazardstatement>
         <p class="- topic/p ">Remove the gland plates and drill
the required holes for the cables connecting to the terminals in the
system. The size of the holes depend on the type and size of the cable
glands used.</p>
         <p class="- topic/p ">Drill the holes in the gland plates so that the
connecting cables can be as straight as possible when attached to
the terminals.</p>
         <p class="- topic/p ">Remove all sharp edges and burrs before installing
the cable glands.</p>
